<h2 class="wp-block-heading faq-heading">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>



<div class="schema-faq wp-block-yoast-faq-block"><div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1623393125914"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Does calisthenics work the lower back?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Yes, calisthenics effectively targets the lower back. Exercises like planks and Supermans strengthen and stabilize the muscles, improving posture and reducing injury risk. These movements are low-impact and ideal for building functional lower back strength.</p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1732786710730"><strong class="schema-faq-question">How to train lower back safely?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Warm up with dynamic stretches, focus on proper form, and start with bodyweight exercises. Gradually progress in intensity while avoiding overloading the spine. Stop if you experience pain and prioritize controlled movements for safe, effective training.</p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1732786720311"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Is it OK to only do calisthenics?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Yes, calisthenics can improve strength, mobility, and endurance. Itâ€™s a versatile workout method that strengthens the lower back and other areas. However, incorporating cardio or stretching enhances fitness and provides a balanced routine.</p> </div> <div class="schema-faq-section" id="faq-question-1732786730359"><strong class="schema-faq-question">Is it OK to workout lower back?</strong> <p class="schema-faq-answer">Yes, training the lower back improves posture, prevents injuries, and supports daily movements like bending or lifting. Safe, targeted exercises strengthen the muscles while reducing strain and promoting spinal stability.</p> </div> </div>
</div></div>
